The acetyl groups (-COCH3) each would increase the melting point due to additional polar interactions and slight increase in molecular weight, estimated at +10°C each. The presence of the 2-nitrophenyl group contributes to the melting point by introducing both a bulky substituent and an electron-withdrawing group, which increases intermolecular forces, particularly dipole-dipole interactions and potential hydrogen bonding, estimated at +20°C. The sulfur atom in the thiadiazole ring also contributes to the melting point by way of Van der Waals interactions, estimated at +5°C. Summing the effects of the individual functional groups to the estimated base melting point of the 1,3,4-thiadiazole gives us the predicted melting point.
Prediction: Approximately 155°C, based on the estimated base melting point of 100-150°C for the thiadiazole ring, +20°C for the two acetyl groups, +20°C for the 2-nitrophenyl group, and +5°C for the sulfur atom in the thiadiazole ring.
